                <head>No. 338.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName> to Mr.
                            <persName type="to">Daggett</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-06-16">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 16, 1883</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 28.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your No. 73
                    of the 18th ultimo, touching the supposed shipments of sugar from China to the
                    Hawaiian Islands, and thence to the United States, duty free. I desire to
                    compliment and to thank you for the very full and ample report which you have
                    submitted upon the subject.</p>
                <p>A copy of your dispatch has been communicated to Mr. Consul Mosby at Hong-Kong,
                    and copies of the entire correspondence sent to the Secretary of the Treasury,
                    for his information.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>FRED’K T. FRELINGHUYSEN.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
